Jan 7 2005	Caswell a good value all things considered	We stayed @ the Caswell Hotel in June 0f 2004 for five days. The carpet was worn and the rooms, stair cases and bathrooms are tiny. However the hotel was clean, the staff friendly and the location quite handy. The breakfast was nothing special but punctual and adequate to start your day. The room was quiet at night the shower was hot and the bed was comfortable. For a first time traveler from the USA it might not be what they expect, but consider that Europe is different from the states and that you are in London. What do you get a tourist hotel for in London for anyway? To sleep in that is about it! We were gone by 09:00 and useually did not return until 20:00. We got what we paid for, a clean quiet place to shower and sleep in. We would stay at Caswell again all things considered.	
Aug 17 2004	Pinch your pennies at the Caswell and you won't regret it.	While the breakfast was unimpressive, the hotel was very quiet, as Frommer's promised, and clean, if shabby. I highly recommend it. The fact that it's on a 24 hour bus line to Covent Garden made it an even better deal, and since we stayed for a week they dropped the price for us. The surrounding neighborhood has all sorts of great, cheap restaurants (including the Cafe Mignon at 41A Warwick way - great breakfast, be sure to eat it on the garden patio behind the restaurant) and thrift shops. If you're blowing your money on other things besides housing (say a week full of theatre), pinch your pennies at the Caswell and you won't regret it.	
Jul 18 2004	This place was cheap! (in all that entails)	My traveling companions and I arrived at two in the morning and were ready to fall into bed and get a good nights rest before beginning our weekend in London. As soon as we laid eyes on the entryway of the Caswell Hotel we were ready to back out slowly for fear of what might attack us when we entered. The carpet was shabby, the walls were dingy, there was a strange aroma lingering in the air and (my favorite part) there was a handwritten sign at the (tiny) check-in desk that said &quot;no visitors after 9:00p.m.&quot; The attendant who greeted us was not welcoming either. His first comment was “I have charged your Visa for the first night. May I have your card so I may charge the rest now?” I said no! But, we were trying to keep expenses down, so we thought we'd at least see the room before we ran screaming from the place. Big mistake. The room was on an upper floor and the staircase leading up was narrow and rickety (even worse than those found in Amsterdam). The room was tiny, but that wasn’t the problem. The room had the vibe of the type of place you’d see in a movie about prostitutes and drug dealers. We were literally afraid to touch the bedspread. The bathroom was a walk-in, back-out deal, with the toilet practically in the shower. If the room had been nice and clean, I could have dealt with the bathroom (and the rest of the hotel for that matter), but in this case it was just one more thing we didn’t like. We fled back downstairs and told the rather stunned attendant we would not be staying in this hotel. I must admit that once he overcame his &quot;hurt feelings&quot; he graciously directed us to a sister property (the Victor Hotel) only a few blocks away (and a few pounds more expensive, but totally worth it) that I would recommend to anyone (Is this a scam they have running?). And because we stayed at a property under the same management, the prepaid night at the Caswell was refunded (thank you). If you are looking for cheap and exciting (?) this may be the hotel for you. Otherwise, spend the extra money for a clean, safe, and pleasant room... somewhere else.	
